// Researched content for mexico-cancun-riviera-maya-c. Written per property.
module.exports = {
  'hilton-cancun-mar-caribe': {
    activities: `Guests split time between family and adult-only pools, a swim-up bar, kids' and teen clubs, a spa and eight restaurants at this newer Hilton on the narrow strip between the Caribbean and Nichupte Lagoon. Off-site, several championship golf courses (Puerto Cancun, Riviera Cancun) sit within a couple of kilometers, and the Hotel Zone's malls and Isla Mujeres ferry are a short drive away, alongside day trips to the El Rey ruins and Xcaret.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hilton Cancun Mar Caribe occupies the strip between the Caribbean Sea and Nichupte Lagoon in the Hotel Zone, a short transfer from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort with kids' and teen clubs, rooms for larger groups, and pets allowed. Ratings run high across the board — room, cleanliness and service all above 9, and a strong 8.5 beach — with pool and atmosphere its comparatively softer categories. As a newer build, the property shows well; expect a lively, amenity-dense Hotel Zone stay rather than a boutique one. November through April is the driest, calmest stretch; hurricane season runs June to November.`,
  },
  'occidental-at-xcaret-destination': {
    activities: `The resort sits inside the larger Xcaret Destination complex, so pools, a swim-up bar, mini golf, tennis, an adult pool and a kids' club are just the on-site layer — guests also get walkable or shuttle access to Xcaret park's underground rivers and cenotes, plus nearby Xel-Ha, Xplor and Xenotes tours. Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue and Tulum's cliffside ruins are both easy day trips from here.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Occidental at Xcaret Destination sits in Solidaridad on the Riviera Maya, roughly 45-60 minutes from Cancun's airport, right alongside the Xcaret eco-archaeological park. It's a large family resort with strong room, location and cleanliness scores. The beach is its clear weak point (a soft 4.8) — this stretch of coast is rockier limestone shelf rather than open sand, which is why many guests spend beach time at Xcaret's own cove instead. Book it for park access and resort scale rather than classic beach lounging. December through April is peak season; hurricane season runs June to November.`,
  },
  'dreams-riviera-cancun-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Kids get a lazy river, pool slide and a dedicated under-4 program alongside a teen club, while the resort's diving operation and swim-up bar anchor the adult side, with nightly entertainment and a nightclub after dark. Off-site, Puerto Morelos' protected barrier-reef waters are excellent for snorkeling and diving close to shore, and Xcaret, Tulum's ruins and Cancun's nightlife are all reachable day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Dreams Riviera Cancun sits in Puerto Morelos, the quieter fishing town midway between Cancun and Playa del Carmen, about 35-45 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family-focused Dreams Unlimited-Luxury property within Hyatt's inclusive collection. The beach is a soft 4.8 — Puerto Morelos' reef keeps the water notably calm, but the sand itself is narrower than Cancun's Hotel Zone. Cleanliness and service are standout categories, both above 9. Good for families wanting a lower-key base with reef access on the doorstep. November through April brings the best reef visibility and driest weather.`,
  },
  'breathless-riviera-cancun-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Breathless leans into its party-resort reputation with a heated pool, swim-up bar and nightclub driving a livelier, DJ-programmed atmosphere than its sister AMResorts brands. Off-site, Puerto Morelos' reef is a short trip for snorkeling and diving, Xcaret and Xel-Ha make for full-day excursions, and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue is a reasonable drive for nightlife and shopping.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Breathless Riviera Cancun sits in the Caracol section of the Puerto Morelos corridor, about 35 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's an adults-only resort, and the Breathless brand is pitched as the liveliest of AMResorts' adult lines — expect a more overt party atmosphere than at neighboring Secrets or Dreams properties. The beach is soft (4.8), consistent with this stretch of coast, but rooms and cleanliness both score in the high 8s and 9s. Best suited to couples prioritizing nightlife and pool scene over quiet sand. November through April is the driest season; June through November is hurricane season.`,
  },
  'villa-del-palmar-cancun-luxury-beach-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Adult and family pools, snorkeling, diving, yoga classes, a kids' club and spa round out the on-site offering, but the standout is location: the resort sits a five-minute walk from the Punta Sam ferry terminal, making Isla Mujeres' Playa Norte and whale-shark tours (June-September) an easy add-on rather than a full-day production.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Villa del Palmar Cancun sits in Punta Sam on the Costa Mujeres side, north of Cancun's Hotel Zone, about 30-40 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family, timeshare-style resort with rooms built for larger groups. Scores are strong across nearly every category — room and cleanliness both above 9, beach at 7.5 — making it one of the more consistently well-reviewed properties on this stretch of coast. The Punta Sam ferry link to Isla Mujeres is a genuine practical advantage. Winter (December-April) is driest; whale shark season runs June through September via Isla Mujeres.`,
  },
  'barcelo-maya-beach': {
    activities: `Part of the sprawling multi-hotel Barcelo Maya complex, guests get a shared stretch of beach plus a waterpark for little kids, mini golf, tennis, diving, snorkeling and a kids' club. Off-site, Akumal's sea-turtle snorkeling cove, Xcaret, Tulum's ruins and the Cozumel ferry for reef diving are all within reach of this stretch of the Riviera Maya coast.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Barcelo Maya Beach sits within the Barcelo Maya complex south of Playa del Carmen near Akumal, roughly 1-1.5 hours from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort sharing beach and facilities with several sister hotels in the same complex. Food, pool and atmosphere all sit in the mid-to-high 6s — typical of a large-scale, buffet-driven operation rather than a boutique one — while location and value hold up well. Good for families wanting variety across a big connected complex. November through April is driest; sargassum can affect the beach some summers.`,
  },
  'hotel-marina-el-cid-spa-and-beach-resort': {
    activities: `The resort's own marina is the real differentiator, running fishing charters and a dive shop alongside multiple pools with slides, kids' and teen clubs, yoga and a spa. Off-site, Puerto Morelos' protected reef — part of the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef system — sits just offshore for diving and snorkeling, with the town's square and seafood restaurants a short golf-cart ride away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Marina El Cid sits in Puerto Morelos, about 35-40 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort built around its own marina, a genuine advantage for fishing and diving trips beyond what most all-inclusives offer. The beach is its softest mark (4.5) — Puerto Morelos' reef-calmed shoreline runs narrower and rockier in patches than Cancun's open sand — but value, cleanliness and service all score well. Best for families or divers who'll use the marina rather than spend all day on the sand. November through April brings calmer seas and better reef visibility.`,
  },
  'villas-hm-palapas-del-mar': {
    activities: `This small, thatched-palapa property leans into Isla Holbox's slower pace: beachfront lounging, bicycle rental (the island is car-free), diving and snorkeling, and a swim-up bar. Off-site, guests explore Holbox's sandy streets by bike or golf cart, join bioluminescent-plankton night tours on the Yalahau lagoon, and — June through September — book whale shark snorkeling trips in the nearby Yum Balam reserve.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Villas HM Palapas del Mar sits on Isla Holbox, reached via Cancun's airport followed by roughly a two-hour drive-and-ferry combination, since no bridge or cars reach the island. This is a small, rustic, palapa-style family property rather than a mega-resort, which is why its amenity list is short by design. It scores well on location and room/cleanliness. Whale shark season (June-September) is the main draw for many visitors; November through February is quieter and cooler, with fewer crowds on the island's sandy lanes.`,
  },
  'mia-reef-isla-mujeres': {
    activities: `The private-island setting on Islote El Yunque is the headline: a beach that scores among the highest marks here, plus a kids' club, diving, watersports rentals, evening entertainment and a spa. Off-site, golf carts and bikes make quick work of Isla Mujeres' Playa Norte and Punta Sur, with reef snorkeling nearby and the frequent Cancun ferry for day trips back to the Hotel Zone.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Mia Reef Isla Mujeres sits on a small bridge-connected islet off Isla Mujeres, reached by ferry from Cancun (about 30-40 minutes to the dock plus the crossing). It's a family resort with a genuinely strong beach (9) and location (9.3) score — a rare combination that reflects the secluded, private-island feel despite proximity to the mainland. Rooms are its comparatively modest category (7.6). Isla Mujeres remains a calmer alternative to Cancun's Hotel Zone. November through April is the driest, most comfortable season.`,
  },
  'bahia-principe-explore-coba': {
    activities: `Set amid jungle, the resort offers a waterpark for little kids, a golf course, casino, tennis, kids' and teen clubs, and an adult pool. Off-site, Akumal's sea-turtle snorkeling cove is a short drive, and both the climbable Coba pyramid — one of the few Mayan sites that still allows climbing — and Tulum's cliffside ruins make for genuine day-trip destinations.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Bahia Principe Explore Coba sits in Chacalal near Akumal on the Riviera Maya, listed nearest to Tulum's newer airport though the transfer still runs about an hour (Cancun's airport is a similar distance). It's a family resort within Bahia Principe's large multi-hotel jungle complex. The beach is the clear weak spot (4.0), typical of this jungle-set stretch versus open Hotel Zone sand, while value and cleanliness score well. Best for families prioritizing pools, golf and nearby ruins over beach time. November through April is the driest window.`,
  },
  'viva-azteca-by-wyndham': {
    activities: `Tennis, beach volleyball, bike rental, a kids' club and mini disco fill the on-site days, with snorkeling and diving off the property's own beach. Off-site, Playacar's own Xaman-Ha Mayan ruins sit within the gated development itself, Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue is a short drive for shopping and restaurants, and the Cozumel ferry runs from town for reef diving.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Viva Azteca by Wyndham sits in Playacar, the gated beachfront district south of central Playa del Carmen, about 45 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort on a genuine white-sand beach (7.3). Food and pool are its softer marks, suggesting a more dated buffet-and-pool setup than newer Riviera Maya builds, but location and value both hold up well. A short walk or cab ride gets guests into Playa del Carmen's town life. November through April is the driest season; June through November is hurricane season.`,
  },
  'hyatt-zilara-riviera-maya': {
    activities: `As an all-suite Zilara property, the emphasis is on a la carte dining, a swim-up bar and evening entertainment in a quieter, adults-only setting rather than a packed activity roster. Off-site, Xcaret and Xel-Ha parks are within easy reach, Playacar's golf course sits nearby, and the Cozumel ferry makes reef diving a realistic day trip.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hyatt Zilara Riviera Maya sits in Solidaridad, near Playacar and Playa del Carmen, about 45 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's the adults-only, all-suite luxury tier within Hyatt's inclusive collection. Room, cleanliness and service all score above 9 — among its strongest marks — while the beach is comparatively soft (5.5), consistent with this section of coast. Suits couples wanting a polished, quiet resort with easy access to Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue for evenings out. November through April is the dry season; June through November brings hurricane risk.`,
  },
  'hideaway-at-royalton-riviera-cancun': {
    activities: `As the adults-only wing within the larger Royalton Riviera Cancun complex, guests get quieter pools and exclusive dining alongside a swim-up bar, nightclub, tennis and spa shared with the main resort. Off-site, Puerto Morelos' reef is close for snorkeling and diving, and Xcaret, Xel-Ha and Playa del Carmen's nightlife are all short drives away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hideaway at Royalton Riviera Cancun sits in Puerto Morelos, about 35 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's the adults-only section within the broader Royalton Riviera Cancun resort, giving access to shared restaurants while keeping its own quieter pool and beach areas. The beach is a genuine weak point here (3.8), one of the softer scores in this corridor, so it suits guests prioritizing pools, dining and nightlife over open sand. Rooms and sleep quality both score well. November through April is the driest stretch.`,
  },
  'secrets-riviera-cancun-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Unlimited a la carte dining without reservation requirements, a swim-up bar, nightclub and spa define the day-to-night rhythm at this upscale adults-only property. Off-site, Puerto Morelos' reef offers close-in diving and snorkeling, Xcaret's eco-park makes a solid day trip, and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue covers nightlife and shopping.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Secrets Riviera Cancun sits in the Caracol section of the Puerto Morelos corridor, about 35-40 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's an adults-only Secrets Unlimited-Luxury property within Hyatt's inclusive collection, pitched a notch more refined than the livelier Breathless brand nearby. The beach is soft (4.8), an area norm, but room, cleanliness and service are consistently among the strongest categories, all above 9. Suits couples who'll prioritize polish and dining over open sand. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'dreams-aventuras-riviera-maya': {
    activities: `Adult and family pools, waterparks for both little and big kids, a kids' club with an under-4 program, diving and snorkeling fill the on-site roster. Off-site, Puerto Aventuras' own marina runs dolphin encounters and boat charters, and Xel-Ha's snorkeling lagoon, Akumal's turtle cove and Tulum's ruins are all nearby.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Dreams Aventuras Riviera Maya sits in Puerto Aventuras, a gated marina town on the Riviera Maya, about an hour from Cancun's airport. It's a family Dreams Unlimited-Luxury property within Hyatt's inclusive collection. The beach is a genuine weak spot (5.3), while food, value and cleanliness all score well. The nearby marina and dolphinarium make it a good pick for families wanting organized water activities beyond the resort's own pools. November through April is best; sargassum can affect the beach in summer months.`,
  },
  'moon-palace-cancun': {
    activities: `One of the coast's largest all-inclusive complexes, with a Flowrider surf simulator, a golf course that has hosted a PGA Tour event, mini golf, watersports rentals, kids' and teen clubs, an arcade, tennis and diving all on-site. Off-site, Xcaret and Xel-Ha parks, Tulum's ruins, and the Isla Mujeres ferry are all within reach.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Moon Palace Cancun sits south of the Hotel Zone toward Puerto Morelos, about 20-30 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a large family Palace Resorts complex spread across multiple sections. The beach is its clear weakest mark (3.8) next to otherwise strong cleanliness, service and room scores (8.8-9), reflecting a narrower, rockier shoreline than the Hotel Zone's classic sand. Best for families who'll spend more time in pools and the extensive on-site sports facilities than on the beach itself. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-yucatan': {
    activities: `A kids' club, diving, watersports rentals, windsurfing and snorkeling anchor the daytime, with a swim-up bar, nightclub and nightly entertainment carrying into the evening. Off-site, Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue is a short drive, Xcaret and Xel-Ha eco-parks make for full-day trips, and the Cozumel ferry opens up reef diving.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Riu Yucatan sits in Playa del Carmen, about 45 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family Riu property with a solid 7.3 beach score and strong value and location marks. Food and pool sit in the mid-6s, typical of Riu's high-volume, buffet-driven model rather than a boutique approach. Rooms for larger groups are available. A dependable, straightforward choice rather than a design-forward one. November through April is driest; hurricane season runs June through November.`,
  },
  'sandos-playacar': {
    activities: `A kids' club, arcade, mini golf, tennis, diving and snorkeling cover the on-site days, with an adult pool, swim-up bar and nightclub for evenings. Off-site, the Xaman-Ha Mayan ruins sit within Playacar itself, Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue is close by, and Xcaret and Xel-Ha are straightforward day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sandos Playacar sits in the gated Playacar district of Playa del Carmen, about 45 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family Sandos resort with a strong 8 beach score for this stretch of coast. Food, pool and atmosphere are its softer marks, in the mid-to-high 6s. Rooms for larger groups are available, and value scores well. Playacar's golf-course setting suits families wanting resort calm with easy access to Playa del Carmen's town center. November through April is the driest window.`,
  },
  'hotel-grand-sunset-princess': {
    activities: `A waterpark for little kids, tennis, kids' and teen clubs, an adult pool and swim-up bar fill out this section of the larger Princess Riviera Maya complex. Off-site, guests can use shared facilities across the connected Princess properties, plus visit Xcaret, Xel-Ha and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue nearby.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Grand Sunset Princess sits in Playa del Carmen, part of the multi-hotel Princess Riviera Maya complex alongside Grand Riviera Princess and its Family Club, about 45 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort where beach and pool sit in the middling range (5.8/6.5) relative to strong room and cleanliness scores. Large in scale, buffet-driven, and best suited to families who want variety across a connected complex rather than a single boutique property. November through April is dry season; June through November brings hurricane risk.`,
  },
  'melia-cozumel': {
    activities: `A kids' club, archery, adult pool, mini golf, tennis, diving, snorkeling and fishing round out the on-site list, but Cozumel's offshore reefs are the real headline — Palancar, Columbia and Santa Rosa walls rank among the Mesoamerican Reef's best diving, with San Miguel town, Chankanaab and Punta Sur parks all short drives away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Melia Cozumel sits on Cozumel island, reached via Cozumel's own airport or ferry from Playa del Carmen. It's a family Melia resort where beach, pool and atmosphere all sit in the high 5s to low 6s — softer marks next to solid location, value and service scores. Cozumel's real strength lies offshore, so this is a better base for divers and snorkelers than for beach lounging. Diving visibility peaks November through May; the whale shark season (June-September) is a Cancun/Isla Mujeres trip rather than a Cozumel one.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-dunamar': {
    activities: `Multiple pools, waterparks for both little and big kids, a kids' club, nightclub and evening entertainment fill the days here. Guests also share party-night programming with sister hotels Riu Palace Costa Mujeres and Riu Latino next door, and Isla Mujeres and Cancun's Hotel Zone nightlife are both reachable by short trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Riu Dunamar sits in Costa Mujeres, roughly 30km north of Cancun's Hotel Zone, about 40 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family Riu resort, part of a three-hotel Riu complex that shares entertainment programming. Beach (7.5), value and cleanliness score solidly, while food and atmosphere are more middling. A quieter, newer-build alternative to the Hotel Zone, with a heated pool useful in cooler months. November through April is the driest stretch.`,
  },
  'almare-a-luxury-collection-resort-isla-mujeres': {
    activities: `This design-led, all-suite property keeps the on-site list quiet and intentional — a beach, yoga, buffet dining, diving and a spa — rather than a packed activity roster. Off-site, guests dive and snorkel the reefs around Isla Mujeres, explore Playa Norte and Punta Sur, and take boat trips back to Cancun's Hotel Zone.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Almare, A Luxury Collection Resort, Isla Mujeres is reached via Cancun's airport, a transfer to a mainland marina, then a boat crossing to the island. It's an adults-only, all-suite property — Marriott's first all-inclusive resort in Mexico — that opened in late 2024, which explains its unusually high, still-fresh ratings across nearly every category (room, cleanliness and service all above 9.2). Small in scale and design-forward rather than amenity-heavy, it suits couples wanting quiet over entertainment. Best visited November through April.`,
  },
  'hotel-belo-isla-mujeres': {
    activities: `This is a genuinely small-scale property — the amenity list runs to little more than a gym and beach access, without kids' clubs or a spa. Off-site, guests walk to nearby Pescador Beach, rent golf carts into Isla Mujeres' town, visit Playa Norte, and book the diving and snorkeling trips that leave from the island's docks.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Belo Isla Mujeres sits on Isla Mujeres, reached via Cancun's airport plus a ferry crossing from the mainland dock roughly 35km away. It's a family-friendly but deliberately small property rather than a big all-inclusive complex, which is why its facilities list is short. Scores lean on rooms, cleanliness and service — all in the high 8s to 9 — rather than amenities. A good pick for travelers wanting Isla Mujeres' slower pace over resort scale. Best visited November through April, though the island stays calmer than Cancun year-round.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-cancun': {
    activities: `An on-site dive program, swim-up bar and the resort's own Pacha discotheque keep both days and nights busy. Off-site, the Hotel Zone's malls, restaurants and clubs line Kukulcan Boulevard nearby, the Isla Mujeres ferry is close, and Xcaret or Chichen Itza make for solid day-trip excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Riu Cancun sits in the Cancun Hotel Zone, adults-only with ID checked at check-in (18+), a short drive from Cancun's airport. Its central Hotel Zone position gives it a location score above 9, putting nightlife and shopping within walking distance. Food and pool are its softer marks, in the mid-6s, against strong location and service. Better suited to couples wanting nightlife access than a quiet retreat — the on-site Pacha club keeps evenings lively. November through April is dry season; June through November is hurricane season.`,
  },
  'royalton-chic-cancun': {
    activities: `A heated pool, swim-up bar, evening entertainment, spa and gym make up the core of this adults-only CHIC property. Off-site, Hotel Zone nightlife and shopping run along Kukulcan Boulevard, the Isla Mujeres ferry is close, and Chichen Itza or Xcaret are realistic day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Royalton CHIC Cancun sits in the Cancun Hotel Zone, a short drive from Cancun's airport. It's Royalton's adults-only, boutique-styled CHIC concept. Scores run strong across the board — location, room and cleanliness all above 9 — with a solid 7.3 beach for the Hotel Zone. A polished, centrally located adults-only option that suits couples wanting both resort comfort and easy nightlife access. November through April brings the driest, most reliable weather.`,
  },
  'sensira-resort-and-spa-riviera-maya': {
    activities: `A water-feature pool area, kids' and teen clubs, an adult pool, tennis, mini golf, yoga and a spa fill the on-site days. Off-site, Puerto Morelos' reef-protected waters are close for snorkeling and diving, and the town's low-key plaza and seafood restaurants are a short trip away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sensira Resort & Spa Riviera Maya sits in Puerto Morelos, about 35-40 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort operated independently of the area's larger chains — a member of Leading Hotels of the World rather than a mass all-inclusive brand — with notably strong room and cleanliness scores (8.9 and 9.1). The beach is its weak point (4.8), typical of the reef-calmed Puerto Morelos shoreline. Suits families wanting a quieter, more design-conscious property than the area's bigger resorts. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'wyndham-grand-cancun-resort-and-villas': {
    activities: `A kids' club, yoga classes, swim-up bar and evening entertainment cover the on-site days. Off-site, Hotel Zone beaches, malls and clubs line Kukulcan Boulevard, the Isla Mujeres ferry is close, and Xcaret or Chichen Itza make for solid day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Wyndham Grand Cancun Resort & Villas sits in the Cancun Hotel Zone — formerly the Omni Cancun Hotel and Villas before its Wyndham rebrand — a short drive from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort with a strong 8 beach score for the Hotel Zone and solid cleanliness, service and room marks. Note that standard rooms cap at three guests, so larger families should look at the villa units. Central for nightlife and shopping along Kukulcan Boulevard. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'breathless-cancun-soul-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Expect the Breathless brand's usual DJ-driven pool and nightclub scene, plus a spa and gym, set on the narrow strip between the Caribbean and Nichupte Lagoon in the Hotel Zone. Off-site, the Hotel Zone's malls and clubs along Kukulcan Boulevard, the Isla Mujeres ferry, and Xcaret or Chichen Itza day trips are all close by.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Breathless Cancun Soul sits in the Cancun Hotel Zone (not Puerto Morelos, despite how it's sometimes filed), a short drive from Cancun's airport, right between the Caribbean and the lagoon. It's an adults-only, high-energy Breathless property. Important timing note: the resort is set to leave Hyatt's portfolio and rebrand as Amare Cancun, Curio Collection by Hilton starting October 31, 2026, so travelers booking stays around that date should confirm which brand will actually be operating. Currently it scores well on rooms, cleanliness and a 7.8 beach — one of its stronger marks. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'catalonia-riviera-maya': {
    activities: `Guests share pools and facilities with sister hotel Catalonia Yucatan Beach next door, spread across several restaurants inside Puerto Aventuras' gated marina community, which has its own golf course and dolphinarium. Off-site, Xel-Ha, Xcaret, Akumal's turtle-snorkeling cove and Tulum's ruins are all short drives away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Catalonia Riviera Maya sits in Puerto Aventuras, a gated marina town on the Riviera Maya roughly midway between Playa del Carmen and Tulum, about an hour from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort sharing beach and amenities with its sister property, Catalonia Yucatan Beach. The beach is soft (4.8), and food, pool and atmosphere all sit in the mid-6s — a value-oriented, mid-tier pick rather than a polished one. November through April is driest; sargassum can affect the beach some summers.`,
  },
  'dreams-sands-cancun-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `A lazy river, a kids' club with an under-4 program, buffet dining and nightly entertainment make up the core of this centrally located Hotel Zone property. Off-site, the shops and clubs along Kukulcan Boulevard are close, the Isla Mujeres ferry is nearby, and Xcaret or Chichen Itza make for solid day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Dreams Sands Cancun sits in the Cancun Hotel Zone, a short drive from Cancun's airport. It's a family Dreams Unlimited-Luxury property within Hyatt's inclusive collection, with a decent 6.5 beach score for the zone. Room and food are its softer marks relative to strong service and location scores. A straightforward, centrally located family base rather than a standout property. November through April is dry season; June through November is hurricane season.`,
  },
  'emporio-cancun': {
    activities: `Three pools and a gym anchor the on-site side of this Hotel Zone property, set near a stretch of beach close to Playa Delfines. Off-site, the El Rey Mayan ruins are a short drive, Cancun's Interactive Aquarium is nearby, and the malls and clubs of the central Hotel Zone strip are close by.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Emporio Cancun sits in Cancun's Hotel Zone, roughly 15-20 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort with a strong 8 beach score, benefiting from proximity to Playa Delfines, one of the Zone's better public beaches. Food and pool are softer, in the mid-6s, typical of an older-style, buffet-driven property. Good value and location for a straightforward Hotel Zone base without the scale of a mega-resort. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'princess-family-club-riviera': {
    activities: `A dedicated family-club pool with kids'-club access, tennis, a teen club, yoga and an adult pool give parents some downtime too. Off-site, guests can use the wider Princess Riviera Maya complex's restaurants and pools, plus visit Xcaret, Xel-Ha and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue nearby.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Princess Family Club Riviera is the family-focused wing of the multi-hotel Grand Riviera Princess/Grand Sunset Princess complex in Playa del Carmen, about 45 minutes from Cancun's airport. Beach and pool are middling (5.8/6.5), while rooms and cleanliness score well. Kid-specific design — bunk beds, pool-adjacent family rooms — makes it a natural fit for families wanting resort-complex scale without a fully separate property. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'platinum-yucatan-princess': {
    activities: `This all-suite, adults-only tier keeps its own separate pools and beach section within the wider Princess complex, with a dining-focused, no-reservations-required approach to restaurants. Off-site, guests can walk over to livelier sister properties or head to Xcaret, Xel-Ha and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Platinum Yucatan Princess is the newest, adults-only all-suite addition to the Princess Riviera Maya complex in Playa del Carmen, about 45 minutes from Cancun's airport. Room and cleanliness score strongly (8.8 each), while the beach is a softer 5.8. It suits couples wanting a quieter, no-minors setting with the option to access the wider complex's restaurants and entertainment. November through April is dry season; June through November brings hurricane risk.`,
  },
  'secrets-mirabel-cancun-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Snorkeling, a swim-up bar, evening entertainment and a spa fill out this recently rebuilt adults-only property. Off-site, Cancun Hotel Zone nightlife and malls are close, the Isla Mujeres ferry runs nearby, and Xcaret, Chichen Itza or Cozumel diving are all realistic excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Secrets Mirabel Cancun sits in Cancun, a short drive from the airport. It's an adults-only Secrets property that reopened in November 2025 after a full rebuild of a decades-old resort into a modern, tropical-minimalist design — which explains its unusually strong, still-fresh ratings, with food, room, cleanliness and sleep quality all above 9. One of the newest additions to Hyatt's inclusive collection in the area. A good choice for travelers wanting a brand-new build in an established location. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'dreams-sapphire-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Renovated rooms, a water park, an oceanfront spa and six restaurants spanning Mexican, French, Pan-Asian and Mediterranean cuisines fill the on-site days. Off-site, Puerto Morelos' reef is close for snorkeling and diving, and Xcaret and Tulum's ruins make for solid day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Dreams Sapphire Resort & Spa (formerly Now Sapphire Riviera Cancun) sits on the Caribbean seafront in Puerto Morelos, about 15-20 minutes from Cancun's airport — closer than most Riviera Maya resorts. It's a family Dreams property within Hyatt's inclusive collection, an AAA Four Diamond recipient. The beach is a soft 5, while food, value and service all score solidly. A convenient pick for families wanting minimal transfer time without sacrificing resort quality. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'fiesta-americana-cozumel': {
    activities: `A kids' club, swim-up bar, diving and snorkeling anchor the on-site offering at this family Mexican-chain property. Off-site, Cozumel's reefs are the real draw — Palancar and Columbia among them — with San Miguel's waterfront and Chankanaab park both easy trips from the resort.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Fiesta Americana Cozumel sits on Cozumel island, reached via Cozumel's own airport. It's a family resort from the Mexican Fiesta Americana chain. The beach is its weakest mark by a wide margin (3.8), while location, cleanliness and service all score well above 8.5. As with most Cozumel properties, the appeal here is the diving and reef access rather than beach lounging. Best diving visibility runs November through May; hurricane season is June through November.`,
  },
  'sunset-marina-resort-and-yacht-club': {
    activities: `This is a marina-side property on the Nichupte Lagoon rather than the open Caribbean, so the on-site focus leans toward the yacht club and lagoon views rather than beach activities. Off-site, the Hotel Zone's beaches, malls and nightlife along Kukulcan Boulevard are a short drive, along with Isla Mujeres ferry trips and Xcaret excursions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sunset Marina Resort & Yacht Club sits in Cancun, a short drive from the airport. It's a family resort, and its beach score (2.0) is the standout figure here — this is a lagoon-facing, marina-side property rather than an open-ocean beachfront one, so guests should plan on using the Hotel Zone's public beaches nearby rather than the resort's own waterfront. Value, service and cleanliness all score reasonably well despite the beach shortfall. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'planet-hollywood-cancun-adult-scene': {
    activities: `Part of the Planet Hollywood complex in Costa Mujeres alongside its Beach Resort and Cancun sister properties, the Adult Scene concept centers on pools, bars and nightlife programming geared toward couples and groups. Off-site, Isla Mujeres and Cancun's Hotel Zone nightlife are both within reach, along with Xcaret and Chichen Itza day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Planet Hollywood Cancun Adult Scene sits in Costa Mujeres, north of Cancun's Hotel Zone, about 40 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's an adults-only resort, part of a multi-property Planet Hollywood complex in the area. Scores are solid and fairly even across categories — beach and room both around 7.5-8.6 — without a standout weak spot, reflecting a newer, well-maintained build in a quieter corridor than the Hotel Zone. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'gr-caribe-by-solaris': {
    activities: `Multiple pools, a heated pool, a kids' club, swim-up bar and spa cover the on-site days at this Hotel Zone property, which sits alongside sister resort Royal Solaris Cancun with shared access arrangements. Off-site, the Hotel Zone's beaches and nightlife, the Isla Mujeres ferry, and Xcaret excursions are all close by.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `GR Caribe by Solaris sits in the Cancun Hotel Zone, a short drive from Cancun's airport, part of the Solaris group of neighboring properties. Beach and location both score well (7.5/8.3), while pool and atmosphere are more middling (mid-6s). A dependable Hotel Zone base with the benefit of shared facilities with its Solaris sister resort next door. November through April brings the most reliable weather; hurricane season runs June through November.`,
  },
  'royal-solaris-cancun': {
    activities: `Designed with families in mind, the resort's pools, buffet dining and evening entertainment sit alongside shared access from neighboring Solaris properties. Off-site, the Hotel Zone's beaches, malls and nightlife along Kukulcan Boulevard are close, and the Isla Mujeres ferry and Xcaret day trips are both easy add-ons.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Royal Solaris Cancun sits in the Cancun Hotel Zone, a short drive from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort, the liveliest and most family-oriented of the neighboring Solaris group. Beach and location score well (7.5/8.3), while food, pool and atmosphere sit in the mid-6s, typical of a large-scale, buffet-driven operation. A solid, central Hotel Zone choice for families. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'cancun-bay-resort': {
    activities: `A single beach amenity anchors a fairly modest facilities list here, reflecting an older-style, no-frills Hotel Zone property rather than an amenity-dense resort. Off-site, the Hotel Zone's malls, restaurants and nightlife along Kukulcan Boulevard are close by, along with the Isla Mujeres ferry and Xcaret day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Cancun Bay Resort sits in the Cancun Hotel Zone, a short drive from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort with modest beach, pool and atmosphere scores (5/5.1/5.8) — its softest categories — reflecting a smaller, older-style property rather than a modern mega-resort. Value and service both score comparatively well, making it a reasonable budget-conscious pick for a central Hotel Zone location rather than a facilities showcase. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'secrets-tulum-resort-and-beach-club': {
    activities: `Set where jungle meets mangrove in Tulum's Aldea Zama district, the resort pairs its main property with a separate beach club a short shuttle away for additional dining and beachfront time. Off-site, Tulum's cliffside ruins and beach are both within a 10-minute drive, and cenote tours around Tulum are an easy add-on.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Secrets Tulum Resort & Beach Club sits in Tulum's Aldea Zama area, about 40 minutes from Tulum's airport or roughly 1 hour 45 minutes from Cancun's. It's an adults-only resort with a distinctly boutique, jungle-meets-sea character rather than a mega-resort feel — pool, atmosphere and sleep quality all score particularly well (8-9.1). The beach score (5.5) reflects that the main property sits back from the shore, with the dedicated beach club covering direct beachfront access. A good fit for couples wanting Tulum's design-forward, bohemian atmosphere within an all-inclusive format. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'hilton-tulum-riviera-maya-resort': {
    activities: `As Hilton's largest resort in the Caribbean and Latin America, the property runs five signature restaurants, extensive pools and a dedicated Family Zone with its own water park playground. Off-site, Tulum's cliffside ruins and beach town are close, and cenote tours and Coba's climbable pyramid make for solid day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hilton Tulum Riviera Maya Resort sits in the Tulum area, listed here via Cancun's airport for transfers. Opened in 2022, this 735-room property is a family resort and one of the newest large-scale builds on this stretch of coast, which shows in its strong room (9.2), cleanliness (9.2) and service scores. The beach is its softer mark (4.0), typical of the Tulum corridor compared to Cancun's Hotel Zone sand. A good choice for families wanting a big, modern resort near Tulum's town and ruins. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'royal-level-at-occidental-cozumel': {
    activities: `This exclusive section of the larger Occidental Cozumel resort layers in a kids' club alongside its own quieter section of beach and pool. Off-site, Cozumel's reefs — Palancar and Columbia among the best-known dive walls on the Mesoamerican Reef — are the main draw, along with San Miguel town and Chankanaab park.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Royal Level at Occidental Cozumel sits on Cozumel island, reached via Cozumel's own airport. It's the elevated, family-friendly tier within the larger Occidental Cozumel resort. Scores are solid and fairly even across categories — location, room and service all in the mid-to-high 8s — without a dramatic weak spot, reflecting the benefit of Royal Level's more curated service level within a larger property. Cozumel's diving and reef access are the destination's real strength. November through May offers the best diving visibility.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-lupita': {
    activities: `A straightforward beach amenity anchors this newer Riu build (opened 2018) in Playacar. Off-site, Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue is a short drive for restaurants and shopping, the Xaman-Ha ruins sit within Playacar itself, and the Cozumel ferry opens up reef diving.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Riu Lupita sits in the Playacar district of Playa del Carmen, about 45 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family Riu property, and the beach is its clear, honest weak point (2.5) — this stretch of shoreline has suffered from erosion since the resort's 2018 opening, and it's a notably lower mark than most nearby resorts. Value still scores well (8.5), and cleanliness and service hold up, but this is not the pick for beach-focused travelers. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'gr-solaris-cancun': {
    activities: `Beachfront pools, seven restaurants and evening entertainment anchor this Hotel Zone property, part of the neighboring Solaris group of resorts. Off-site, the Hotel Zone's malls and nightlife along Kukulcan Boulevard are close, and the Isla Mujeres ferry and Xcaret day trips are easy additions.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `GR Solaris Cancun sits in the Cancun Hotel Zone, a short drive from Cancun's airport. It's part of the Solaris group of neighboring properties in the zone. Beach and location score well (7.5/8.4), while food, pool and atmosphere sit in the mid-to-high 6s, consistent with a large, buffet-driven resort. A dependable central Hotel Zone base rather than a design-forward pick. November through April is the driest, most reliable season.`,
  },
  'dreams-natura-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `An aqua park and lazy river, jungle-inspired grounds and a kids'-under-4 program fill the days at this recently reworked property. Off-site, Puerto Morelos' protected reef is close for snorkeling and diving, and Xcaret and Tulum's ruins are both realistic day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Dreams Natura Resort & Spa sits in Puerto Morelos, about 15 minutes from Cancun's airport — one of the closer Riviera Maya resorts to the airport. It's a family property (previously operating as Hyatt Ziva Riviera Cancun before its relaunch as Dreams Natura) within Hyatt's inclusive collection, with jungle-facing grounds and a Caribbean-facing white-sand beach. The beach still scores on the softer side (4.5), typical of this section of coast, though room and cleanliness both score well above 8.5. November through April is the dry season.`,
  },
  'melia-casa-maya-cancun': {
    activities: `A water park, four restaurants and The Level's elevated concierge service anchor this Hotel Zone property, part of Melia's broader Paradisus Cancun complex. Off-site, the Hotel Zone's malls and nightlife along Kukulcan Boulevard are close, and Isla Mujeres and Xcaret are both easy day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Melia Casa Maya Cancun sits in the Cancun Hotel Zone, a short drive from Cancun's airport, part of Melia's wider Paradisus Cancun complex. It's a family resort with a solid 7.5 beach score and strong location (8.7). Food, pool and atmosphere sit in the mid-6s, typical of a large buffet-driven property rather than a boutique one. The Level rooms offer an upgraded, more personalized tier for those wanting extra service within the same resort. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'occidental-costa-cancun': {
    activities: `Set near the mouth of the Nichupte Lagoon, this Hotel Zone property keeps its amenity list simple, centered on beach access near Linda and Las Perlas beaches. Off-site, the Hotel Zone's malls and clubs along Kukulcan Boulevard are a short drive, and Isla Mujeres and Xcaret are both realistic day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Occidental Costa Cancun sits at Kukulcan Boulevard's Km 4.5 in the Cancun Hotel Zone, near the mouth of the Nichupte Lagoon, a short drive from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort with a decent 6.8 beach score. Food, pool and atmosphere are its softer marks, in the low-to-mid 6s, suggesting a more dated, no-frills property compared to newer Hotel Zone builds. Value and cleanliness both score reasonably well. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'catalonia-yucatan-beach': {
    activities: `Sharing pools and facilities with sister property Catalonia Riviera Maya next door, guests get a private beach within the gated Puerto Aventuras marina community, which also has its own golf course and dolphinarium. Off-site, Xel-Ha, Xcaret and Tulum's ruins are all short drives away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Catalonia Yucatan Beach sits in Puerto Aventuras, a gated marina town on the Riviera Maya, about an hour from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort forming a combined complex with sister property Catalonia Riviera Maya. The beach is soft (4.8), and food, pool and atmosphere all sit in the mid-6s — a value-oriented, mid-tier pick rather than a polished one. November through April is driest; sargassum can affect the beach some summers.`,
  },
  'royalton-splash-riviera-cancun': {
    activities: `The headline here is one of the Caribbean's larger on-site water parks — 14 slides, splash pads and two lazy rivers — alongside supervised kids' clubs and a teens area. An optional Diamond Club section adds private pools and butler service. Off-site, Puerto Morelos' reef and Xcaret are both within reach.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Royalton Splash Riviera Cancun sits in Puerto Morelos, about 35 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort built specifically around its water park, part of Royalton Luxury Resorts (Marriott's Autograph Collection). The beach is a clear weak point (4.0), while pool scores comparatively well (7.6) given the water park's scale. Best suited to families prioritizing water-park time over beach days. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'allegro-playacar': {
    activities: `Two pools — one lively with an animation team, one quiet — a disco, theater, kids' club with its own mini pool, tennis and beach volleyball make up this budget-friendly beachfront property. Off-site, Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue is a short drive, and the Xaman-Ha ruins sit within Playacar itself.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Allegro Playacar sits in the gated Playacar district of Playa del Carmen, about 45 minutes from Cancun's airport. It's a family resort under Barcelo's budget-friendly Allegro brand, popular for beachfront weddings and honeymoons. Beach scores well (7.8) while food, pool and atmosphere sit in the low-to-mid 6s, reflecting its value-tier positioning. Good for travelers wanting Playacar's beach and gated calm without paying for a higher-end brand. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
  'allegro-cozumel': {
    activities: `A pirate-themed water park anchors the kids' club here, alongside four additional pools including a quiet pool and a swim-up bar. Off-site, Cozumel's reefs are the main draw for diving and snorkeling, with San Miguel town and Chankanaab park both easy trips from the resort.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Allegro Cozumel sits on San Francisco Beach, Cozumel, about 25 minutes from Cozumel's airport. It's a family resort under Barcelo's budget-friendly Allegro brand (formerly marketed as Occidental Allegro). Scores sit in the high 7s to low 8s across most categories without a standout weak spot, reflecting a straightforward, value-tier property. Best for travelers prioritizing Cozumel's diving and reef access over resort polish. November through May offers the best diving visibility.`,
  },
  'grand-park-royal-cozumel': {
    activities: `Two towers of rooms overlook two infinity pools and whirlpools, with a secluded beach club reached through a private underpass, plus a kids' club, fitness center and spa. Off-site, Cozumel National Marine Park's coral reefs and Chankanaab National Park are both just minutes away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Grand Park Royal Cozumel sits in San Miguel de Cozumel, reached via Cozumel's own airport. It's a family resort from the Mexican Park Royal chain, within walking distance of Cozumel's main shopping and entertainment areas. The beach is its softest mark (4.0), while location, cleanliness and service all score well above 8. A convenient, walkable base for divers wanting easy access to Cozumel's reefs and town center. November through May is best for diving visibility.`,
  },
  'sandos-caracol-eco-resort': {
    activities: `The eco-park concept is the draw: a jungle-set lazy river runs guests through mangrove forest roots on the "Jade River Adventure," a 29-slide water park covers thrills for kids and adults, and eco tours connect to nearby cenotes and lagoons. Off-site, Playa del Carmen's town center is a short drive, with Xcaret and Tulum's ruins as further day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sandos Caracol Eco Resort sits in Playa del Carmen, about 45 minutes from Cancun's airport and 15 minutes from downtown Playa del Carmen. It's a family resort built around sustainability and nature immersion — solar power, water treatment systems, and jungle/mangrove surroundings define the property more than a conventional beachfront setup. The beach is a clear weak point (3.8), so this suits families prioritizing the eco-park and water park over open sand. Rooms and value both score reasonably well. November through April is the driest season.`,
  },
}
